WEBVTT

00:06.441 --> 00:08.617
- Previously
on "Briarpatch"...

00:08.660 --> 00:10.097
- We have to talk.
Meet me in Packingtown.

00:10.140 --> 00:11.663
- The boss wants a meeting
with your candy-ass senator.

00:11.707 --> 00:13.578
- Well, the senator is meeting
with a homicidal monster,

00:13.622 --> 00:15.450
so it has to be
someplace secret.

00:15.493 --> 00:16.842
How did you get
wrapped up in this?

00:16.886 --> 00:18.583
- I'm his attorney.

00:18.627 --> 00:19.932
- You just announced
your candidacy for mayor.

00:19.976 --> 00:22.152
Mayor Salazar is a friend.
When you come to me

00:22.196 --> 00:24.024
for a favor, make sure
you bring something

00:24.067 --> 00:26.026
of equal or greater value
to exchange.

00:26.069 --> 00:27.157
- You ever deal
with the Bains boy?

00:27.201 --> 00:28.767
- Candy Bar?
Oh, no.

00:28.811 --> 00:31.161
He gave up his inheritance,
this house,

00:31.205 --> 00:33.163
and he went just plain loco.

00:33.207 --> 00:35.078
- Bitch,
my gang will fuck you up.

00:35.122 --> 00:37.950
- You're not a gang.
You're just bored.

00:37.994 --> 00:39.256
- [grunts]
Let's finish this.

00:39.300 --> 00:41.824
You and I are gonna catch
Clyde Brattle.

00:41.867 --> 00:43.173
- You, me, and what army?

00:43.217 --> 00:44.653
- We hatched ourselves a plan.

00:44.696 --> 00:46.524
He'd buy up as much
of Packingtown as he could.

00:46.568 --> 00:47.699
I'd run for mayor

00:47.743 --> 00:49.527
to make something worthwhile
out of it all.

00:49.571 --> 00:52.052
I know what you are, Gene.
You're a contract killer.

00:52.095 --> 00:53.096
[both grunting]

00:53.140 --> 00:56.099
[explosion]
[crowd screaming]

00:56.143 --> 00:58.884
- Felicity's boyfriend
did kill her.

00:58.928 --> 01:00.625
And it was you.

01:00.669 --> 01:01.887
[yelps]

01:01.931 --> 01:06.762
[tense music]

01:06.805 --> 01:09.243
[tires squealing]

01:09.286 --> 01:11.201
[radio static]

01:11.245 --> 01:14.161
[sweeping big band music]

01:14.204 --> 01:21.342
♪

01:24.823 --> 01:26.651
- Dad...
[voice echoes]

01:29.089 --> 01:31.395
We're going too fast.

01:31.439 --> 01:33.919
Mom, can't you hear me?

01:33.963 --> 01:36.096
[engine revving]

01:36.139 --> 01:37.793
We're going too fast.
[echoing] Fast...

01:39.664 --> 01:40.665
We're going too--

01:40.709 --> 01:43.233
[brakes squeal]

01:43.277 --> 01:45.496
- [laughs]

01:45.540 --> 01:47.890
- Why can't you understand
this?

01:49.196 --> 01:51.459
- It isn't up to you, kid.

01:51.502 --> 01:53.678
- I decide how fast we go.

01:53.722 --> 01:55.115
- [laughs]

01:55.158 --> 01:57.204
[engine revving]

01:59.597 --> 02:02.731
[silence]

02:05.299 --> 02:06.822
- Felicity?

02:06.865 --> 02:08.215
- Pick?

02:08.258 --> 02:11.174
[soft, dreamy music]

02:11.218 --> 02:16.788
♪

02:16.832 --> 02:18.573
- [grunts]

02:18.616 --> 02:21.271
- [laughing]

02:21.315 --> 02:23.621
- [gasping]

02:23.665 --> 02:26.450
[crazed laughter increases]
[Allegra grunting]

02:30.193 --> 02:33.153
[screaming]

02:33.196 --> 02:35.894
[dramatic music]

02:35.938 --> 02:37.983
♪

02:38.027 --> 02:39.724
[muted clattering]

02:39.768 --> 02:41.204
[radio tunes]

02:41.248 --> 02:44.207
[eerie funky music]

02:44.251 --> 02:50.779
♪

02:50.822 --> 02:53.825
[Candido's
"Thousand Finger Man"]

02:53.869 --> 02:55.305
♪

02:55.349 --> 03:00.919
- ♪ Candido

03:00.963 --> 03:03.444
♪

03:03.487 --> 03:07.230
♪ Candido

03:07.274 --> 03:11.234
[light drumming]

03:11.278 --> 03:12.844
♪ Candido

03:12.888 --> 03:16.108
- Captain Colder!

03:16.152 --> 03:18.241
A drink.

03:18.285 --> 03:20.069
- Oh, uh...no, thanks.

03:20.112 --> 03:22.027
I don't--

03:22.071 --> 03:23.333
okay.

03:23.377 --> 03:27.250
[light pop music
continues in background]

03:27.294 --> 03:34.039
♪

03:34.083 --> 03:35.519
- To endings.

03:35.563 --> 03:37.565
[glasses clink]
[chuckles]

03:39.784 --> 03:40.829
Ah.

03:40.872 --> 03:42.352
- [slurping]

03:43.745 --> 03:45.877
- With Jake Spivey
taken care of,

03:45.921 --> 03:49.098
our business here
for the moment is concluded.

03:49.141 --> 03:51.753
- I'm sorry I wasn't able
to kill Spivey personally.

03:51.796 --> 03:53.363
- [tuts]

03:53.407 --> 03:55.365
- Sir--
- Sidney.

03:55.409 --> 04:02.546
♪

04:05.767 --> 04:07.247
- Oh.

04:10.859 --> 04:13.775
[tense music]

04:13.818 --> 04:18.780
♪

04:18.823 --> 04:20.390
- It's not enough.

04:22.523 --> 04:25.047
- Excuse me?
- I don't want money.

04:25.830 --> 04:29.312
I had a life here, Mr. Brattle.
A new life.

04:29.356 --> 04:32.707
I didn't come here to run away.
I came here to start over.

04:32.750 --> 04:35.449
When Mr. Gattopardo told me
about you,

04:35.492 --> 04:37.625
he said you helped the people
who helped you.

04:37.668 --> 04:39.888
Give me another chance.

04:39.931 --> 04:41.411
I have a lot to offer.

04:41.455 --> 04:43.152
I'm good police,
I'm a good man--

04:43.195 --> 04:44.327
- No, no, no.

04:44.371 --> 04:47.330
You were a crooked cop
in debt to the mob,

04:47.374 --> 04:49.158
a debt that was transferred
to me.

04:49.201 --> 04:50.768
I gave you equipment,
money, time.

04:50.812 --> 04:51.943
What did you do?

04:51.987 --> 04:53.858
You took a bomb
that was meant for Spivey

04:53.902 --> 04:55.338
and you used it
on the Dill girl.

04:55.382 --> 04:56.905
Very messy.

04:56.948 --> 04:58.385
- I had to!

04:58.428 --> 04:59.864
She was on to me.

04:59.908 --> 05:01.736
[glass clicks down]

05:03.564 --> 05:07.002
- That was not a clean-up job.

05:07.045 --> 05:08.612
That was punishment.

05:08.656 --> 05:11.441
She saw beneath your mask.

05:11.485 --> 05:13.443
Self-delusion is the bane

05:13.487 --> 05:15.358
of an enlightened society,
Captain.

05:15.402 --> 05:18.666
I truly hope
you fully understand that.

05:18.709 --> 05:20.624
- Please, I'm begging you.

05:20.668 --> 05:22.974
Things just kinda got away
from me.

05:23.018 --> 05:24.759
I can still make a mark.

05:24.802 --> 05:28.197
- Oh, my boy.

05:28.240 --> 05:31.722
You have made a mark.

05:31.766 --> 05:34.464
Now you just have to
live with it.

05:38.686 --> 05:41.079
- [grunts] Uhh--
[tattoo gun buzzing]

05:43.168 --> 05:46.650
[grunts]
[buzzing continues]

05:46.694 --> 05:48.217
- [muttering]
It's gonna be pretty.

05:48.260 --> 05:49.523
It's gonna be pretty.

05:49.566 --> 05:52.569
- When you work for me,
it's permanent.

05:52.613 --> 05:53.962
We'll be in touch.

05:54.005 --> 05:57.008
- Plagues of locusts
and boils,

05:57.052 --> 05:59.359
rivers thick with blood.
[shoveling sounds]

05:59.402 --> 06:02.971
The ancient ones witnessed
these signs of the end times,

06:03.014 --> 06:05.321
and friends,
as we pass through

06:05.365 --> 06:08.237
into the chaos
of the unknown,

06:08.280 --> 06:11.458
I urge you to stay tuned.

06:11.501 --> 06:14.286
I may upset you.
I may frighten you.

06:14.330 --> 06:16.114
- Can I get a cigarette?

06:16.158 --> 06:18.682
- But I will never
lie to you.

06:18.726 --> 06:22.033
- I'll tell you what.

06:22.077 --> 06:24.209
You answer a question,

06:24.253 --> 06:25.907
you can have one.

06:28.213 --> 06:30.999
You're gonna die out here,
you know that, right?

06:31.042 --> 06:33.436
So I gotta ask--

06:33.480 --> 06:36.396
how the hell is he worth it?

06:37.571 --> 06:39.703
- This idiot's made
a lot of mistakes.

06:39.747 --> 06:41.705
But being my friend
isn't one of them.

06:41.749 --> 06:43.533
[man continues on radio
in background]

06:43.577 --> 06:46.797
- Oh, hell, Pick.
That's all right.

06:48.233 --> 06:49.409
- Now, you see, sweetie,

06:49.452 --> 06:51.541
if I offered
this friend of yours

06:51.585 --> 06:53.543
20 bucks right now

06:53.587 --> 06:57.721
to put the bullet
in your head himself,

06:57.765 --> 07:01.246
he'd probably negotiate it
down to 15.

07:01.290 --> 07:03.118
- Don't be jealous, Harley.

07:03.161 --> 07:04.685
I'll kill you for free.

07:04.728 --> 07:06.382
- Though I really
oughta give him a knife

07:06.426 --> 07:09.864
because he's best
at stabbing people in the back.

07:12.519 --> 07:15.652
- Clyde isn't your daddy,
Harley.

07:15.696 --> 07:19.569
He ain't never
gonna muss your hair or...

07:19.613 --> 07:22.050
tell you
your pecker's big enough.

07:22.093 --> 07:23.486
'Cause it ain't.

07:23.530 --> 07:25.053
- You got soft hands,
Spivey!

07:25.096 --> 07:26.707
- Man, you're wearing
a fanny pack!

07:26.750 --> 07:28.186
- What--
- Can I get a light?

07:37.326 --> 07:39.110
- Now,

07:39.154 --> 07:41.548
don't you know
that's bad for you?

07:41.591 --> 07:44.202
- That's the other thing
Jake Spivey knows.

07:44.246 --> 07:46.378
- What's that?

07:46.422 --> 07:49.947
- How to enjoy the things
that are bad for you.

07:49.991 --> 07:52.472
- [screaming]

07:52.515 --> 07:55.953
[intense music]

07:55.997 --> 07:57.520
♪

07:57.564 --> 07:59.696
[gasping]

07:59.740 --> 08:01.916
[both grunting]

08:01.959 --> 08:04.658
- Pull it tight!
Pull it tight!

08:04.701 --> 08:07.965
[both grunting,
breathing hard]

08:08.009 --> 08:14.885
♪

08:16.713 --> 08:19.499
- Keys for the van are here
but not the handcuffs.

08:20.891 --> 08:24.634
[soft, dramatic music]

08:24.678 --> 08:27.332
[huffs]
Phone's dead.

08:27.376 --> 08:28.812
See, you only been dead
a minute

08:28.856 --> 08:31.511
and you're still
pissing me off!

08:31.554 --> 08:33.643
Come on.
You're gonna have to drive.

08:33.687 --> 08:38.866
♪

08:38.909 --> 08:41.956
[grunting]

08:41.999 --> 08:43.958
Come on, girl.
I got you, come on.

08:44.001 --> 08:45.655
- Okay.

08:45.699 --> 08:47.657
- Shut the door, door, door.

08:47.701 --> 08:54.838
♪

08:55.883 --> 08:57.841
[engine turns over]

08:57.885 --> 09:00.191
[both breathing hard]

09:05.196 --> 09:08.243
- Say, uh, this the first time
you've been behind the wheel

09:08.286 --> 09:09.636
since your parents...

09:09.679 --> 09:11.986
- I'm fine.
I'm fine.

09:13.596 --> 09:15.946
We have to get back.

09:15.990 --> 09:19.167
The person who killed Felicity
is Gene Colder.

09:20.124 --> 09:21.038
- Colder?

09:21.082 --> 09:23.127
- He was Brattle's inside man.

09:23.171 --> 09:26.783
He came here to kill you,
Jake.

09:26.827 --> 09:29.046
The only person
who matters here is him.

09:30.265 --> 09:32.920
So you need to get on board.
And if not--

09:32.963 --> 09:35.836
- Now wait a minute, Pick.
You're goin' too fast.

09:35.879 --> 09:37.620
- What did you say?
- Pick, look out!

09:37.664 --> 09:39.927
[glass shattering]

09:45.976 --> 09:48.675
[solemn music]

09:48.718 --> 09:55.856
♪

10:16.137 --> 10:19.096
- [soft inhale]

10:30.368 --> 10:31.979
- Come on.

10:32.022 --> 10:33.197
Come on!

10:33.241 --> 10:34.721
[both grunting]

10:34.764 --> 10:37.593
- Come on.
- Ah--

10:37.637 --> 10:44.687
♪

10:45.819 --> 10:50.519
[announcer in background]

10:50.562 --> 10:52.652
- Oh, God damn it.

10:52.695 --> 10:55.263
- Where's Allegra?

10:55.306 --> 10:57.961
She was at the school
when the bus exploded.

10:58.005 --> 10:59.746
Now she's not answering
her phone.

10:59.789 --> 11:01.748
And she got a meeting
she can't miss.

11:01.791 --> 11:03.880
- Well, lucky for her,
she's got people like you

11:03.924 --> 11:05.969
keeping track of her calendar.

11:06.013 --> 11:08.450
Along with whatever else it is
you do.

11:08.493 --> 11:10.017
- That attack was targeted.

11:10.060 --> 11:12.106
Somebody wanted Allegra
and Jake Spivey out the picture

11:12.149 --> 11:13.803
and I'm willing to bet
that that person

11:13.847 --> 11:16.240
was Clyde Brattle.

11:16.284 --> 11:17.677
- Who's that now?

11:19.679 --> 11:22.638
- You don't know
who Clyde Brattle is?

11:22.682 --> 11:25.685
- I have no idea
who you're talking about.

11:25.728 --> 11:27.077
- [laughs]

11:27.121 --> 11:29.166
This town is full of liars.

11:29.210 --> 11:31.081
Of course you wanna be
their mayor.

11:31.125 --> 11:35.695
- This town is full of unsolved
Goddamn explosions, Mr. Singe.

11:35.738 --> 11:38.001
And we're hemorrhaging blue.

11:38.045 --> 11:40.438
You know I lost Sergeant Mock
in that attack?

11:40.482 --> 11:42.440
A decent man with a family

11:42.484 --> 11:45.487
who put his head down
and did his damn job?

11:45.530 --> 11:48.011
So if you'll excuse me.
[knock on door]

11:48.055 --> 11:50.231
Is that ready for me to sign?
- Yes, ma'am.

12:04.071 --> 12:07.727
This is all of it.
Everything he owns.

12:09.990 --> 12:11.426
[slam echoes ominously]

12:15.822 --> 12:17.998
- So what are you planning
to do?

12:20.348 --> 12:21.915
To Colder, I mean.

12:21.958 --> 12:23.568
When you catch him.

12:23.612 --> 12:25.092
- Why?

12:26.833 --> 12:29.749
- Well, if you're planning
on killing a man,

12:29.792 --> 12:31.141
it ain't the sort of thing

12:31.185 --> 12:33.274
that keeps
till the last minute.

12:35.102 --> 12:37.757
- Are you actually lecturing me
on planning right now?

12:37.800 --> 12:39.193
You?

12:39.236 --> 12:41.325
- I just don't wanna see you
make a mistake.

12:42.805 --> 12:44.720
Like 12 years ago.

12:44.764 --> 12:47.767
- I went to prison for you,
Jake.

12:47.810 --> 12:50.030
I took the fall
for your fool idea.

12:50.073 --> 12:51.901
- Whoa, whoa, whoa, whoa,
my idea?

12:51.945 --> 12:53.337
- Yes.
- Oh, come on, now.

12:53.381 --> 12:55.122
You're the one
that started spilling

12:55.165 --> 12:56.645
about this dirty congressman

12:56.688 --> 12:58.255
who needed to be taught
a lesson.

12:58.299 --> 13:00.040
- I didn't suggest
blackmailing him.

13:00.083 --> 13:02.520
- You didn't have to.

13:02.564 --> 13:05.262
'Cause I did what I always do.

13:05.306 --> 13:09.092
Give you permission to do
all those bad things

13:09.136 --> 13:13.053
that are rattling around
in that pretty little head.

13:13.096 --> 13:15.533
- I went to jail.

13:15.577 --> 13:18.145
And you vanished.

13:19.886 --> 13:22.149
- Look, all I'm saying is...

13:24.064 --> 13:28.416
You've been running from home
for two decades.

13:28.459 --> 13:29.983
- And you?

13:30.026 --> 13:32.159
- I'm trying to make one.

13:35.075 --> 13:38.339
Why don't you join me?

13:38.382 --> 13:40.428
Oh, come on.
You know it makes sense.

13:42.865 --> 13:44.519
Us.

13:46.129 --> 13:48.915
- If you're trying to tell me
that you love me,

13:48.958 --> 13:51.526
you picked a lousy time.

13:54.877 --> 13:56.270
- I told you I loved you

13:56.313 --> 13:58.533
when I took a bullet for you,
Pick.

14:03.103 --> 14:06.019
[tense music]

14:06.062 --> 14:12.329
♪

14:12.373 --> 14:14.636
- We need to
get back to town now.

14:14.679 --> 14:16.333
Any idea which way?

14:18.118 --> 14:19.554
[sighs] Come on.
- Ow!

14:28.824 --> 14:32.349
- So this is everything that,
uh, Harold had for Allegra

14:32.393 --> 14:33.873
about Raytek?

14:33.916 --> 14:35.657
- As far as I know.

14:35.700 --> 14:38.878
I told him to give her
some essential oils.

14:38.921 --> 14:41.228
But he said that he didn't like

14:41.271 --> 14:44.622
to mix business
with aromatherapy.

14:44.666 --> 14:46.320
Which I can respect.

14:48.322 --> 14:51.107
Do you know his pillow
still smells like menthol?

14:53.675 --> 14:56.939
- Um, did Harold...

14:56.983 --> 14:59.028
does he still have
that little bug that--

14:59.072 --> 15:00.725
he calls it his baby?

15:00.769 --> 15:03.685
- Uh, yeah, that's right here
in this box.

15:03.728 --> 15:07.036
You can take it if you like.
The decrypting software too.

15:07.080 --> 15:09.952
I never wanna see any of that
ever again.

15:09.996 --> 15:12.607
- Okay, thank you.

15:13.825 --> 15:16.002
- What are you gonna do
with it?

15:16.045 --> 15:18.395
- Whatever it takes.

15:18.439 --> 15:21.703
- There's a fire in your eyes,
Mr. Singe.

15:21.746 --> 15:23.966
I like it.

15:24.010 --> 15:27.230
But if it ever creeps down
to your belly, you let me know.

15:27.274 --> 15:29.450
I'll mail you
some milk thistle.

15:29.493 --> 15:31.582
Clean it right up.
- [laughs]

15:43.464 --> 15:45.770
[glass cracks]

15:45.814 --> 15:48.599
- Don't mind your loafers
too much, Mr. Lapin.

15:48.643 --> 15:52.255
Rats are mostly gone now,
due to the asbestos.

15:56.129 --> 15:58.392
- I suppose it requires
some creative thinking,

15:58.435 --> 16:01.786
but I believe I can see
what it is you have planned.

16:01.830 --> 16:03.701
- Oh, I hope you can,

16:03.745 --> 16:06.139
'cause it's big, it's bright,

16:06.182 --> 16:08.968
and it's positively dripping
with dollar signs,

16:09.011 --> 16:11.013
and it can be yours.

16:11.057 --> 16:13.537
Papers are all signed
and deeded.

16:13.581 --> 16:15.452
Your senator
could use this land

16:15.496 --> 16:18.629
to scratch the itchiest backs
in Texas.

16:18.673 --> 16:21.371
He could have a new airport
named after his donors.

16:21.415 --> 16:22.982
Hell, he could have
a waste dump

16:23.025 --> 16:25.288
named after his enemies.

16:25.332 --> 16:28.291
As long as I get
what I need in return.

16:28.335 --> 16:32.121
- Well, well, well.
I am impressed, Chief Raytek.

16:32.165 --> 16:35.690
I didn't expect a policewoman
to be so adaptable.

16:37.997 --> 16:39.520
- [laughs]

16:39.563 --> 16:40.738
You know anything

16:40.782 --> 16:42.566
about earthquake architecture,
Mr. Lapin?

16:42.610 --> 16:43.393
- Earthquake?

16:43.437 --> 16:45.047
- San Francisco, California.

16:45.091 --> 16:46.701
Beautiful city out there
by the bay.

16:46.744 --> 16:48.572
You been?

16:48.616 --> 16:50.183
[laughs]

16:50.226 --> 16:52.750
Cold pilsners and crab backs.
The best, right?

16:52.794 --> 16:54.665
- Mmm.
- Problem is...

16:54.709 --> 16:57.059
this is just about
the fifth or sixth version

16:57.103 --> 16:59.714
of San Francisco
they've gone and built.

16:59.757 --> 17:03.152
Until a smart cookie
by the name of John Blume

17:03.196 --> 17:05.285
figured out that you can't
fight earthquakes

17:05.328 --> 17:08.070
by making things stronger.

17:08.114 --> 17:10.594
You fight 'em
by making 'em looser.

17:10.638 --> 17:13.554
Buildings that roll
with the punches.

17:15.512 --> 17:18.298
So nowadays,
big one hits the coast,

17:18.341 --> 17:20.387
those buildings rattle
and shake

17:20.430 --> 17:22.128
like they caught the vapors,

17:22.171 --> 17:24.130
but they don't crumble

17:24.173 --> 17:26.045
no matter how bumpy it gets.

17:26.088 --> 17:28.047
[funky music]

17:28.090 --> 17:30.266
- And that's you, is it,
Chief--

17:30.310 --> 17:35.184
or should I say Mayor Raytek?

17:35.228 --> 17:37.056
- It damn sure is.

17:37.099 --> 17:43.323
♪

17:45.803 --> 17:48.719
[tense desert music]

17:48.763 --> 17:55.683
♪

18:14.223 --> 18:16.051
- Hold on, hold on.

18:16.095 --> 18:18.619
I can't...I can't...

18:18.662 --> 18:20.142
- Ah...uhh--

18:20.186 --> 18:22.927
- [groaning]
Ah...ah...

18:22.971 --> 18:24.364
Ah!

18:24.407 --> 18:27.323
[both breathing heavily]

18:27.367 --> 18:34.504
♪

18:53.480 --> 18:56.439
- You know what happened
to Felicity...

18:56.483 --> 18:58.659
it ain't your fault, Pick.

19:02.184 --> 19:04.795
- Yes, it is.

19:04.839 --> 19:07.146
I left.

19:12.194 --> 19:14.457
You know how on airplanes,

19:14.501 --> 19:17.504
when they tell you to put
your oxygen mask on first?

19:19.941 --> 19:21.116
So you can help someone

19:21.160 --> 19:23.510
who's too little
to help themselves?

19:28.123 --> 19:30.517
I put my mask on first, Jake.

19:34.260 --> 19:37.785
I got out...

19:37.828 --> 19:39.047
so she could live.

19:39.090 --> 19:42.355
[solemn music]

19:42.398 --> 19:43.834
♪

19:43.878 --> 19:47.925
- No, you...

19:47.969 --> 19:50.841
you did that
so you could live.

19:50.885 --> 19:54.018
♪

19:54.062 --> 19:56.717
That ain't no crime.

19:58.197 --> 20:01.722
- I spent 20 years running
from this Goddamn town.

20:01.765 --> 20:07.510
♪

20:07.554 --> 20:10.774
She must've thought
I was running from her.

20:10.818 --> 20:16.040
♪

20:16.084 --> 20:19.522
I thought she'd be better off
without me.

20:19.566 --> 20:22.395
I thought
she'd make better choices.

20:23.526 --> 20:25.833
[sobbing]
Oh, God.

20:31.230 --> 20:33.841
She needed me.

20:37.323 --> 20:39.412
And I wasn't there.

20:45.722 --> 20:47.463
When she died...

20:47.507 --> 20:51.075
♪

20:51.119 --> 20:52.990
She was alone.

20:58.866 --> 21:00.781
- It's done, Pick.

21:05.264 --> 21:07.309
It's done.

21:07.353 --> 21:10.617
- [labored breaths]

21:14.360 --> 21:18.146
- If Felicity really
wanted help,

21:18.189 --> 21:20.931
she would've called someone.

21:20.975 --> 21:25.109
♪

21:25.153 --> 21:27.460
- She did call someone.

21:27.503 --> 21:31.290
[wind whistling]

21:39.428 --> 21:42.388
[hopeful music]

21:42.431 --> 21:49.569
♪

21:51.179 --> 21:52.876
Jake?

21:52.920 --> 21:57.098
♪

21:57.141 --> 21:58.229
Jake.

21:58.273 --> 22:00.710
- Huh.
- Jake, come on.

22:00.754 --> 22:02.233
Jake, come on.
- [grunts]

22:02.277 --> 22:04.975
- Come on.

22:05.019 --> 22:06.499
Come on!

22:09.197 --> 22:10.851
- [grunts]

22:10.894 --> 22:17.814
♪

22:24.691 --> 22:26.954
- The natural state
of the world

22:26.997 --> 22:29.478
is not order.

22:29.522 --> 22:32.176
It is chaos.

22:32.220 --> 22:35.615
The ancient deity Atum
created our reality

22:35.658 --> 22:37.791
as a mirror of the divine sky,

22:37.834 --> 22:40.968
but it is a cracked mirror

22:41.011 --> 22:43.971
which will one day be
subsumed entirely

22:44.014 --> 22:46.669
by the sun god Ra.

22:46.713 --> 22:50.064
Indeed, Ra will destroy
the world,

22:50.107 --> 22:53.197
but it was
in his benevolent eye,

22:53.241 --> 22:57.376
itself a wayward goddess,
that created human life

22:57.419 --> 22:59.726
and allowed us this,

22:59.769 --> 23:03.033
our temporary dream

23:03.077 --> 23:05.862
of control.

23:05.906 --> 23:07.734
Of course,
it was the Nubian people

23:07.777 --> 23:10.606
that told a different tale.

23:11.825 --> 23:13.696
They spoke of a dangerous time

23:13.740 --> 23:16.656
when the Eye of Ra
went missing.

23:16.699 --> 23:19.049
Many brave heroes
lost their lives

23:19.093 --> 23:22.618
in pursuit of her,
and when she was finally found,

23:22.662 --> 23:25.404
wandering in distant lands,

23:25.447 --> 23:27.188
the Eye of Ra was benevolent
no more.

23:27.231 --> 23:28.407
- What the--
- Shh.

23:28.450 --> 23:30.409
- Instead,

23:30.452 --> 23:34.717
she had taken the form
of a wild feline,

23:34.761 --> 23:37.503
a fire-breathing jungle cat

23:37.546 --> 23:41.158
who had surrendered
to the very chaos

23:41.202 --> 23:43.552
she was meant to subdue.

23:43.596 --> 23:46.120
Do you understand the power

23:46.163 --> 23:47.948
of an open eye?

23:47.991 --> 23:49.558
Can you look

23:49.602 --> 23:52.082
without blinking

23:52.126 --> 23:54.215
into the madness?

24:00.569 --> 24:03.485
Time has come to answer.

24:03.529 --> 24:07.054
[birds cawing]

24:07.097 --> 24:09.970
[both gulping]

24:11.319 --> 24:13.843
- You're dehydrated.

24:13.887 --> 24:16.150
More than you know.
Drink it all.

24:16.193 --> 24:18.152
- [soft belch]

24:20.023 --> 24:22.461
Now, who are you?

24:22.504 --> 24:24.463
- Who are you, tin man?

24:24.506 --> 24:25.899
- I'm Jake Spivey.

24:25.942 --> 24:29.555
- I know your mask name,
tin man.

24:29.598 --> 24:31.905
You live in my house.

24:34.516 --> 24:36.866
- Holy shit.

24:38.651 --> 24:41.001
Candy Bar Bains?

24:41.044 --> 24:43.917
- That was my mask name, yeah.
Before I lifted it.

24:46.528 --> 24:48.008
- Well,

24:48.051 --> 24:52.012
guess there's something
to be said for downsizing.

25:06.940 --> 25:08.985
- Help me get him to the table.

25:12.206 --> 25:14.338
Just right here.

25:14.382 --> 25:16.166
- [grunting]

25:16.210 --> 25:17.298
- Upsy daisy.

25:17.341 --> 25:18.952
- [yelps]

25:18.995 --> 25:21.563
[grunting]

25:21.607 --> 25:23.347
- Sugar corrodes, you know.

25:23.391 --> 25:25.785
Eats away at flesh and bone.

25:25.828 --> 25:27.830
My family may as well
have made their fortune

25:27.874 --> 25:29.832
peddling battery acid.

25:29.876 --> 25:31.355
I had no choice
but to abandon them

25:31.399 --> 25:35.011
while there was still something
left in me to save.

25:35.055 --> 25:36.883
- [groans]

25:38.406 --> 25:41.975
- That wound's a metaphor.
You realize that, right?

25:42.018 --> 25:44.760
- There's metal in my leg!

25:46.762 --> 25:49.504
- Are you vaccinated?

25:49.548 --> 25:50.636
- Yeah.

25:50.679 --> 25:52.072
- Well, then you have metal

25:52.115 --> 25:54.161
coursing through every vein
in your body, tin man.

25:57.251 --> 25:59.645
All prisons are structures,
right?

25:59.688 --> 26:01.690
Ergo,
all structures are prisons

26:01.734 --> 26:03.213
That's strong if you need it.

26:03.257 --> 26:07.130
The media, the so-called
criminal justice system, kale--

26:07.174 --> 26:09.480
we think that we control
these things,

26:09.524 --> 26:11.874
that we invented them,

26:11.918 --> 26:16.400
but the truth is they were here
long before we were.

26:16.444 --> 26:17.619
Good?
- Uh-huh.

26:17.663 --> 26:18.838
- All right.

26:18.881 --> 26:20.666
- [screams]
- Ooh.

26:20.709 --> 26:22.015
I'd tell you
to close your eyes, tin man,

26:22.058 --> 26:23.538
but you've never opened 'em.

26:23.582 --> 26:25.235
- Pick.
Pick!

26:25.279 --> 26:29.152
Aaaaaaaah!

26:29.196 --> 26:31.024
[moaning, groaning]

26:34.288 --> 26:36.899
- Look at me.

26:36.943 --> 26:39.598
Yeah, you'll be fine.

26:39.641 --> 26:41.643
[sniffs]
At least on the outside.

26:41.687 --> 26:44.820
- [gasping]

26:56.658 --> 26:59.618
[shady funky music]

26:59.661 --> 27:06.755
♪

27:08.583 --> 27:10.150
[clanking]

27:10.193 --> 27:12.892
- Though no suspect
has yet been named

27:12.935 --> 27:15.546
in last night's attack
on San Bonifacio High,

27:15.590 --> 27:18.027
we've been told to stand by
for an official statement

27:18.071 --> 27:20.377
from Police Chief Eve Raytek.

27:20.421 --> 27:22.684
We now return to
Detective E.Q. Lateral

27:22.728 --> 27:24.904
in the third
of "A Third Man."

27:24.947 --> 27:27.254
- Well, Malgebra Capone,

27:27.297 --> 27:30.126
you tried to divide
and conquer,

27:30.170 --> 27:33.652
but there's one thing you
forgot to account for--me.

27:33.695 --> 27:36.132
- You got it all wrong,
Lateral.

27:36.176 --> 27:38.526
[continues in background]

27:38.569 --> 27:41.485
[tense music]

27:41.529 --> 27:44.706
♪

27:44.750 --> 27:46.360
- Where's Allegra?
Hmm?

27:46.403 --> 27:47.578
- Ms. Dill has been AWOL

27:47.622 --> 27:50.712
since approximately 10:10
Monday night.

27:50.756 --> 27:52.845
- This isn't like her.

27:54.585 --> 27:56.544
[knocking]

27:56.587 --> 27:59.547
[tense music]

27:59.590 --> 28:06.685
♪

28:10.253 --> 28:12.560
Mr. Brattle.

28:12.603 --> 28:14.605
- Senator Ramirez,

28:14.649 --> 28:16.390
an overdue pleasure.

28:16.433 --> 28:23.397
♪

28:23.440 --> 28:26.748
Cactus juice?

28:26.792 --> 28:28.054
[laughs]

28:28.097 --> 28:30.534
- I've heard a lot about you,
Mr. Brattle.

28:30.578 --> 28:32.275
Some good.

28:32.319 --> 28:34.016
Most of it bad.

28:34.060 --> 28:36.715
- I find binary distinctions
exhausting.

28:36.758 --> 28:38.020
- Mm.

28:38.064 --> 28:40.370
As exhausting
as living in a van?

28:40.414 --> 28:41.894
- [laughs]

28:41.937 --> 28:43.504
I will admit

28:43.547 --> 28:45.985
my present circumstances are
not up to my usual standard,

28:46.028 --> 28:48.814
but that is why I am so eager

28:48.857 --> 28:51.991
to hear what it is
you plan to offer me.

28:52.034 --> 28:53.993
- We're not here
to make you an offer.

28:54.036 --> 28:55.255
We represent the government

28:55.298 --> 28:57.736
of the United States
of America,

28:57.779 --> 29:00.782
not the mob.

29:00.826 --> 29:03.567
- Senator Ramirez...

29:03.611 --> 29:06.179
you're an Exeter man, yes?

29:07.658 --> 29:09.530
As am I.
- Huh.

29:10.705 --> 29:12.576
- Remember our motto?

29:12.620 --> 29:14.753
Non sibi.

29:14.796 --> 29:17.277
"Not for oneself."

29:19.801 --> 29:22.369
- Meaning?
- Meaning...

29:22.412 --> 29:25.415
all I am here to do
is help you.

29:25.459 --> 29:26.939
- [laughs]

29:26.982 --> 29:29.202
He's here to help us.

29:29.245 --> 29:32.031
- I'm not like Jake Spivey.

29:32.074 --> 29:34.773
I don't need to debase myself
to get what I want.

29:34.816 --> 29:36.035
- Really?

29:36.078 --> 29:37.253
Because I was under
the impression

29:37.297 --> 29:38.777
that you were willing to, uh,

29:38.820 --> 29:40.169
what was it, Cyrus?

29:40.213 --> 29:41.649
- "Take your medicine."

29:41.692 --> 29:42.998
- [laughs]
Well...

29:43.042 --> 29:45.305
a spoonful of sugar
and all that.

29:45.348 --> 29:46.828
[laughs]

29:53.008 --> 29:55.794
In exchange for immunity,

29:55.837 --> 29:58.622
you can have those names.

29:58.666 --> 30:01.321
Along with a piece of advice:

30:01.364 --> 30:03.845
I am far more valuable
as a friend

30:03.889 --> 30:06.717
than as an enemy.

30:06.761 --> 30:08.676
- This is
the Secretary of Defense.

30:08.719 --> 30:11.331
- Mm-hmm.
And two senators.

30:11.374 --> 30:14.203
Along with that much-admired
admiral,

30:14.247 --> 30:17.467
the one that's married
to the condiments heiress.

30:17.511 --> 30:19.339
- Do you really have the goods
on these men?

30:21.254 --> 30:24.083
- I made them all rich.

30:24.126 --> 30:28.000
The events of Al-Namur
did not happen in a vacuum.

30:29.653 --> 30:31.873
[softly] And I can show you
the receipts.

30:31.917 --> 30:33.657
- These four men
are my competition

30:33.701 --> 30:35.485
for next year's nomination.

30:35.529 --> 30:38.575
- And all four
bound for disgrace or prison

30:38.619 --> 30:41.796
with the evidence I have,

30:41.840 --> 30:44.320
leaving the field clear
for you.

30:44.364 --> 30:46.061
That is,

30:46.105 --> 30:48.498
if we have a deal.

30:48.542 --> 30:55.462
♪

30:58.378 --> 31:00.336
- Well, I think we just might.

31:00.380 --> 31:03.774
♪

31:03.818 --> 31:05.080
- [laughs]

31:05.124 --> 31:06.821
♪

31:06.865 --> 31:08.475
[laughs]

31:08.518 --> 31:09.693
- Let's go.

31:09.737 --> 31:14.437
♪

31:20.269 --> 31:23.185
- Hey, um...

31:23.229 --> 31:25.927
can you help us
get back to town?

31:25.971 --> 31:27.886
- The bombs, right?
Your sister?

31:29.539 --> 31:32.847
You know
there were two bombers, right?

31:32.891 --> 31:34.762
- Yes.

31:34.805 --> 31:36.416
How do you know?

31:36.459 --> 31:38.461
- Game theory.

31:40.420 --> 31:41.464
Mescaline.

31:41.508 --> 31:42.596
- Okay.

31:42.639 --> 31:44.119
- The first bomb
was a crime of passion.

31:44.163 --> 31:46.339
It was thoughtless, abrupt,

31:46.382 --> 31:47.949
foolish, really.

31:47.993 --> 31:49.516
Second bomb was the opposite.

31:49.559 --> 31:51.605
It was rational, precise,

31:51.648 --> 31:53.912
built of a different material
but made to mimic the original.

31:53.955 --> 31:55.739
Now what does that tell us?

31:55.783 --> 31:57.524
- That the second bomb

31:57.567 --> 31:59.308
was meant to distract
from the first.

31:59.352 --> 32:02.224
- And the question that
capitalism demands we ask is?

32:02.268 --> 32:04.487
- Who profited
from the distraction?

32:04.531 --> 32:06.837
- Very good.

32:06.881 --> 32:08.404
Second bomb was Semtex,
of course,

32:08.448 --> 32:10.885
like the one that I used
at the zoo.

32:10.929 --> 32:11.930
- You?

32:11.973 --> 32:14.933
- No, no, no, no!

32:14.976 --> 32:17.936
Do not hang
a cop-killer trip on me.

32:17.979 --> 32:20.025
My bomb was a weapon
of liberation,

32:20.068 --> 32:21.200
not of punishment.

32:21.243 --> 32:23.637
I am a conduit of freedom,

32:23.680 --> 32:25.595
a breaker of chains.

32:34.039 --> 32:35.736
Try one of these.

32:38.130 --> 32:40.697
Of course, not all chains
are visible.

32:40.741 --> 32:42.264
Once I freed those animals,

32:42.308 --> 32:44.527
their fate was in
their own hands, or paws.

32:44.571 --> 32:46.965
[laughs]

32:47.008 --> 32:49.663
That camel out there?

32:49.706 --> 32:50.751
It's here by choice.

32:54.015 --> 32:56.148
- Ahh...

32:56.191 --> 32:58.977
- Freedom isn't a gift.
It's a responsibility.

33:03.677 --> 33:06.158
- Hey, is that, uh...

33:06.201 --> 33:09.030
- And sometimes,

33:09.074 --> 33:11.815
we choose to remain in bondage

33:11.859 --> 33:14.035
because it feels safer.

33:14.079 --> 33:18.300
Love and hate, truth and lies--
those aren't opposites.

33:18.344 --> 33:21.347
Those are ropes that bind us
to our oppressors.

33:23.653 --> 33:27.179
- The only way to beat a system
is to...

33:27.222 --> 33:29.790
remove yourself from it
entirely.

33:30.834 --> 33:32.184
- Yeah, that's right.

33:32.227 --> 33:34.142
- Look, the only thing
I wanna remove myself from

33:34.186 --> 33:35.709
is this Goddamn desert.

33:35.752 --> 33:37.406
- There's a bus
three clicks that way.

33:37.450 --> 33:39.017
If you hurry, you can catch it.

33:42.542 --> 33:43.717
- Thank you.

33:46.067 --> 33:48.461
- Is your eye open now?

33:51.507 --> 33:54.032
Good.

33:54.075 --> 33:56.251
Don't eat the kale.

33:56.295 --> 33:58.036
It's how they spread
Lyme disease.

33:58.079 --> 34:00.908
[metal clinking]

34:00.951 --> 34:04.085
[tense music]

34:04.129 --> 34:11.614
♪

34:20.580 --> 34:22.799
- Good to be home.

34:26.586 --> 34:29.937
Don't tell me that freak
out there got to you.

34:29.980 --> 34:32.766
You ain't going all tinfoil hat
on me, are you, Pick?

34:35.464 --> 34:37.988
Come on.
I'll get us a car.

34:38.032 --> 34:41.731
We can hole up at my house
till we figure out next moves.

34:41.775 --> 34:43.255
- I'm gonna walk.

34:43.298 --> 34:46.040
- Pick, we just gone done
walking a Goddamn marathon.

34:46.084 --> 34:48.651
[laughs]
Why not take it light?

34:50.044 --> 34:52.090
- Because I'm not done yet.

34:55.136 --> 34:58.226
- But it ain't safe alone.

34:58.270 --> 35:01.490
[sighs] Pick.
They're trying to kill us.

35:05.668 --> 35:07.235
Shit.

35:07.279 --> 35:09.672
- We have to talk.

35:09.716 --> 35:12.284
I need help.

35:12.327 --> 35:14.155
No, not there.
It's not safe.

35:14.199 --> 35:16.636
- [whooping]
Meet me in Packingtown.

35:16.679 --> 35:18.855
[laughter]

35:19.639 --> 35:23.730
- We have to talk.
I need help.

35:23.773 --> 35:25.035
No, not there.

35:25.079 --> 35:27.429
- Yeah, yeah!
- [giggling]

35:27.473 --> 35:28.691
- Meet me in Packingtown.

35:28.735 --> 35:30.650
- Yee hee hee hee.

35:30.693 --> 35:33.609
- What you doin'
out here alone?

35:33.653 --> 35:37.613
[laughter]

35:37.657 --> 35:40.834
- What the fuck
happened with you?

35:51.932 --> 35:53.673
Who's bored now, bitch?

35:53.716 --> 35:56.284
[breathing hard]

36:00.462 --> 36:03.248
Hey...
I'll do it.

36:05.075 --> 36:06.947
What the fuck?

36:06.990 --> 36:09.515
You're supposed to be scared.

36:11.038 --> 36:13.345
Guys, let's go.

36:15.085 --> 36:17.087
Crazy bitch.

36:17.131 --> 36:19.873
Come on, guys.
Hurry up.

36:19.916 --> 36:21.222
Come on!

36:21.266 --> 36:23.920
Crazy bitch!

36:25.313 --> 36:27.446
- We have to talk.
- Crazy bitch!

36:27.489 --> 36:30.231
- I need help.

36:30.275 --> 36:32.668
No, not there.
It's not safe.

36:34.366 --> 36:36.237
Meet me in Packingtown.

36:36.281 --> 36:37.804
[elevator dings]

36:37.847 --> 36:40.850
[solemn music]

36:40.894 --> 36:45.594
♪

36:49.598 --> 36:51.687
- There's something
that I need you to hear.

36:55.909 --> 36:58.259
- Come, Sidney.

36:58.303 --> 37:01.131
Oh, there is one more thing.
- Yes?

37:01.175 --> 37:03.264
- I hope your investigator

37:03.308 --> 37:05.397
isn't an essential part
of this deal.

37:05.440 --> 37:07.703
- Ms. Dill is very much
under our control.

37:07.747 --> 37:09.575
- No doubt,
but she does know

37:09.618 --> 37:11.925
about our business together.

37:11.968 --> 37:15.537
And perhaps things
that might be a...liability

37:15.581 --> 37:18.279
for a presidential campaign?

37:19.280 --> 37:22.370
- What are you suggesting?

37:22.414 --> 37:24.938
- Would it be a problem
for either of you gentlemen

